This document will bring up some common flaws that are often a problem in security departments, things that are easily avoided.

[head=3]Commuication, Communication, Commuication![/head]
[bold]Distress Signal[/bold]
Make sure to label your distress trigger so that your colleagues know who is in danger.

[bold]Call and Response[/bold]
If someone calls out X crime at Y department, make sure to respond. "On my way", "Heard", or anything similar is worth gold. Even if you aren't going to go to help, at least let them know it was heard.     

[bold]Relevance[/bold]
Try to keep the security channel clean. All officers do not need to know that the clown is mouthin' off. [italic]See Marking system below[/italic]

[head=3]Orderly HQ is an effective HQ[/head]
[bold]Evidence[/bold]
Try to put gathered evidence or contraband in lockers! If the Warden isn't around, do it yourself! It can be a good idea to put several items in a bag and lable the bag after the person they were taken from, so they are easy to recover later. 

[bold]Keep it Clean[/bold]
If you see trash or debris, clean it up. If the HQ is full of random things, "I left X on the counter for you" becomes an insurmountable task! 

[head=3]Use Technology![/head]
[bold]Criminal History[/bold]
Take a few seconds to enter criminal history EVERY time you return to the HQ. It can be as simple as "Contra: X item" or "Trespass: X department/area", and dont forget to add arrests to criminal history too(ideally with sentence time)
This will make it so much easier to keep track of repeat offending, make the warden happy, and help determine who has before commited a crime before and may have again.

[bold]Marking system[/bold]
We can not stress enough how important it is to keep marks up to date. It helps the whole department to keep track of what is going on. It is all too often the case that people are detained, sentenced and released while being on wanted for the entire duration. 
